<center><div style="background:rgba(5,5,0,0.5); padding:10px; text-align:center; font-size:30px; font-family:Coiny; color:#FEB05D; letter-spacing:2px; border-radius:30px; width:300px">'''Overview'''</div></center>


All exploration through Level 208 has shown a modern-styled interior consisting of 21st century architecture with 1970's / hippie era decorum. Exteriors of Level 208 suggest the time to be permanently noontime, and discernible signs show the level's name to be '''Orange Offices LLC.''' Further connections to a place within [[The Frontrooms|baseline reality]] have remained unsuccessful, alongside leaving the building through otherwise typical exits, as all exterior exits seem to be anonymously reinforced.

Since its discovery in the early 1700s, documentation of the level has been largely consistent, with no signs of change over its recorded history<ref>outside of human activity</ref>. Alongside the level's unchanging environment, chemical and otherwise normal changes also slow down or completely stop while in Level 208, especially in relation to decay and aging. Wanderers have been tested to show significantly less effects of aging while in the level, possibly a result of it being locked in time. 

Imports into Level 208<ref>namely, food and food ingredients</ref> remain largely orchestrated and managed by [[The K4|Kappa IV]], with additional help from the various group populations within it. General civilization is spread across the various main sections, with residency for affiliated and unaffiliated parties. While the main sections have been outlined, the variety of structures and locations within Level 208 makes outlining all of them borderline impossible.

<center><div style="background:rgba(5,5,0,0.5); padding:10px; text-align:center; font-size:25px; font-family:Coiny; color:#FEB05D; letter-spacing:2px; border-radius:30px; width:250px">'''The Offices'''</div></center>


[[File:TheOrangeOffices.png|thumb|right|300px|An officespace in Level 208]] Connected to each other through large wooden pathways, offices make up the most of the buildings in Level 208. Each cubicle is 4m by 2.5m in size and are connected by an open air passageway to the corridors. The interior layout of the cubicle vary significantly, though many share common functions. Each consists of two seats, a wall-bound shelf, a secondary platform on the desk, and at least one plant. 

The two seats are always the same no matter the room layout, with one being a rolling desk chair, and the other is a small couch. They show no signs of wear or damage, and have restoration properties if someone damages them. This restorative property is also true for the other furniture in the office.

[[File:OfficeLayout.png|thumb|300px|left|A map of one of the layouts]]
The desk has two forms, one being a standard table desk, and the other being l-shaped. It appears to be randomized too, with each room also choosing the alignment and formatting of most features in the cubicle. On the desk is a variety of office supplies, often beings pens, lamps, staplers, etc. In some cases, these desks can be replaced with [[Object List|various objects]], such as [[Object 42|Spice of Life]] and [[Object 2|Level Keys]]. Dangerous items have also been spotted on the desks, but are less rare. 

With the most up to date logs of Level 208, no office has the exact same layout. The possibility of one being duplicated is still presumed true, as much of the offices remain inaccessible. These unknown offices are difficult to reach because of no defined bridge to them. These bridges are essential to the pathways in Level 208. 

<center><div style="background:rgba(5,5,0,0.5); padding:10px; text-align:center; font-size:25px; font-family:Coiny; color:#FEB05D; letter-spacing:2px; border-radius:30px; width:250px">'''The Bridges'''</div></center>


[[File:OrangeOfficesBirdges.png|A photo of one of the bridges in Level 208|thumb|300px|left]]
The only means of travel between offices and food courts is through the bridges. The flooring and walls are all made of hickory wood planks painted gray. The transparent panels which make up the railing are also consistent to wood, and all tests have pointed to it acting the same as standard wood. The paneled rails are sunken into the ground 0.15m and extend upward 0.8m. In the rare case that these panels are broken, large sects of orange tape cover the spot, usually displaying warning signs.

Signs have been noted embedded into the aforementioned walls. Most of these are small red and white signs, believed to be emergency exit indicators. Most of them, however, point in logically impossible directions, such as completely vertical or moving in a diagonal direction. Since they are embedded into the wall, trying to change them has remained unsuccessful. The other main type of signs in Level 208 are shift papers. Placed once every 3 offices, the names and dates on them are inconsistent. Many have random text characters, dates set in the far past or future, and time slots that are not of equal amount. The offices go upward to 20 floors, with bridges connecting the two sides of the bridge. Additionally, all doors within the Bridges are made of the same transparent wood and have a double swing mechanism.

<center><div style="background:rgba(5,5,0,0.5); padding:10px; text-align:center; font-size:25px; font-family:Coiny; color:#FEB05D; letter-spacing:2px; border-radius:30px; width:250px">'''The Cafeteria'''</div></center>


[[File:Lemontea.png|thumb|250px|right|Lemon Tea for 3 Vouchers]]
In between bridge rooms, large cafeterias are placed. The cafeterias are estimated to be 2 times the width of the bridges, and connect to 4 other bridges. Each cafeteria offers a small variety of foods in the standard breakfast lunch and dinner categories seen in typical restaurants. Every cafeteria only has one restaurant in it, which supplies the above menu. All ingredients needed to produce the food remain in mint condition while in storage, only decaying outside of it. Surrounding the restaurant is a large number of tables and chairs.

Out of the 26 discovered restaurants, 20 of them are ran by a group known as ''Windless Kitchen''. The group prepares meals of wanderers in exchange for Almond Vouchers and other resources. In other cases, the wanderer is often required to make the food themself, so interaction with the group is often needed to travel through Level 208. All plant life found in the level always produces citruses, even if logically impossible for the plant. This is the same for the food, which, despite the variance, usually consists of citrus based foods. Supposedly, specific farms have been made in the level to quickly produce these foods, but nothing has been confirmed.

